    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Painful Decision</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Susanne Fischer letter says there are very good reasons for adopted children not to seek out their biological parents that were not addressed in June 3 article</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Adoptee-Rights Hero Who Knows All the Arguments'' (Public Lives column, June 3):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Adoptee-Rights Hero Who Knows All the Arguments'' (Public Lives column, June 3):</p>
        <p>I don't believe that Helen Hill knows all the arguments. How would she feel if a child she had given up for adoption showed up at her doorstep?</p>
        <p>Placing a child that you have carried for nine months in the arms of another family has to be the most gut-wrenching decision one can make. To then have this person walk back into your life opens a Pandora's box of problems.</p>
        <p>As a happy, healthy adopted child myself, I see absolutely no need to disrupt the lives of people who have  already made one of the toughest choices of their lives.</p>
        <p>SUSANNE FISCHER  New York, June 5, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
